{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492946","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492946"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:50:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:50:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1189"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1189","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1189"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.29,0.18,0.45,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1189"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"85722"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1189","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1189"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1189"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70021"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"97"},{"type":"tags","id":"1109"},{"type":"tags","id":"1126"},{"type":"tags","id":"4789"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6931"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7324"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29401"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44502"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"85722","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/85722"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn otherwise well 22-year-old woman presents with a two week history of severe anal pain, associated with the passage of small volume bright red blood at the time of defecation. These symptoms started after a severe bout of constipation when she was on holiday. She has been using stool softeners and warm baths since returning with minimal improvement in the pain. She is afebrile and all vitals are within normal limits. Abdominal examination is normal, as is visual inspection of the perineum. She refuses a digital rectal examination as she says this is too painful.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sphincterotomy","Local anaesthetic cream","Sitz baths","Glyceryl trinitrate ointment","Indomethacin suppositories"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is almost certainly suffering with an acute anal fissure as a result of recent constipation. Once a fissure has developed the anal sphincter may go into spasm, which further perpetuates the problem and compromises healing. Reducing the spasm is useful when conservative measures have proven ineffective. This can be achieved with the topical application of \u003Cstrong\u003Eglyceryl trinitrate ointment\u003C/strong\u003E \u2013 a smooth muscle relaxant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile, 50% of acute anal fissures resolve with conservative management including \u003Cstrong\u003Estool softeners\u003C/strong\u003E and sitz/salt baths, these strategies have proven ineffective in the above case. They will still be helpful in aiding defecation but are not the most appropriate management strategy to advise in this instance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELocal anaesthetic creams\u003C/strong\u003E are often used for both anal fissures and haemorrhoids and may provide symptomic relief for patients but they do not relax the anal sphincter. Overuse of topical anaesthetic can lead to dermatitis and skin irritation and should be avoided.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA lateral internal \u003Cstrong\u003Esphincterotomy\u003C/strong\u003E is a viable treatment option for chronic anal fissures however the case presented is of an acute fissure and therefore is inappropriate in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIndomethacin suppositories\u003C/strong\u003E are a non-steroidal anti-inflammatory (NSAID) drug indicated in the management of inflammatory conditions such as gout and osteoarthritis. They are also contraindicated in patients with a history of proctitis or recent rectal bleeding and therefore are not an appropriate management option for this patient.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Where conservative management has proven ineffective, topical glyceryl trinitrate is first line for the management of acute anal fissures.","Anal fissures typically present with severe pain on defecation and small volume bright red rectal bleeding."],"references":["Hwang, SH. Trends in treatment for hemorrhoids, fistula, and anal fissure\u201d J anus rectum colon. 2022;6(3);150-8. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9328791/","Drugs.com. Indomethacin suppository package insert/prescribing information. https://www.drugs.com/pro/indomethacin-suppository.html"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70021"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1189"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70021","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/70021"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-17T18:34:16+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-17T18:35:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1189"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"85722"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"headin